[src:preact/introduction] The **Document Object Model** (**DOM**) connects web pages to scripts or programming languages by representing the structure of a document—such as the HTML representing a web page—in memory.
[src:preact/introduction] Usually it refers to JavaScript, even though modeling HTML, SVG, or XML documents as objects are not part of the core JavaScript language.
[src:preact/introduction] DOM methods allow programmatic access to the tree.
[src:preact/introduction] With them, you can change the document's structure, style, or content.
[src:preact/introduction] Nodes can also have event handlers attached to them.
[src:preact/introduction] The Document Object Model (DOM) is a programming interface for web documents.
[src:preact/introduction] It represents the page so that programs can change the document structure, style, and content.
[src:preact/introduction] The DOM represents the document as nodes and objects; that way, programming languages can interact with the page.
[src:preact/introduction] A web page is a document that can be either displayed in the browser window or as the HTML source.
[src:preact/introduction] In both cases, it is the same document but the Document Object Model (DOM) representation allows it to be manipulated.
[src:preact/introduction] As an object-oriented representation of the web page, it can be modified with a scripting language such as JavaScript.
[src:preact/introduction] All of the properties, methods, and events available for manipulating and creating web pages are organized into objects.
[src:preact/introduction] For example, the `document` object that represents the document itself, any `table` objects that implement the `HTMLTableElement` DOM interface for accessing HTML tables, and so forth, are all objects.
[src:preact/introduction] The DOM is built using multiple APIs that work together.
[src:preact/introduction] The core DOM defines the entities describing any document and the objects within it.
[src:preact/introduction] This is expanded upon as needed by other APIs that add new features and capabilities to the DOM.
[src:preact/introduction] For example, the HTML DOM API adds support for representing HTML documents to the core DOM, and the SVG API adds support for representing SVG documents.
[src:preact/introduction] A **DOM tree** is a tree structure whose nodes represent an HTML or XML document's contents.
[src:preact/introduction] Each HTML or XML document has a DOM tree representation.
[src:preact/introduction] Although the above tree is similar to the above document's DOM tree, they're not identical, as the actual DOM tree preserves whitespace.
[src:preact/introduction] When a web browser parses an HTML document, it builds a DOM tree and then uses it to display the document.
[src:preact/introduction] The previous short example, like nearly all examples, is JavaScript.
[src:preact/introduction] That is to say, it is *written* in JavaScript, but *uses* the DOM to access the document and its elements.
[src:preact/introduction] The DOM is not a programming language, but without it, the JavaScript language wouldn't have any model or notion of web pages, HTML documents, SVG documents, and their component parts.
[src:preact/introduction] The document as a whole, the head, tables within the document, table headers, text within the table cells, and all other elements in a document are parts of the document object model for that document.
[src:preact/introduction] They can all be accessed and manipulated using the DOM and a scripting language like JavaScript.
[src:preact/introduction] The DOM is not part of the JavaScript language, but is instead a Web API used to build websites.
[src:preact/introduction] JavaScript can also be used in other contexts.
[src:preact/introduction] For example, Node.js runs JavaScript programs on a computer, but provides a different set of APIs, and the DOM API is not a core part of the Node.js runtime.
[src:preact/introduction] The DOM was designed to be independent of any particular programming language, making the structural representation of the document available from a single, consistent API.
[src:preact/introduction] For more information on what technologies are involved in writing JavaScript on the web, see JavaScript technologies overview.
[src:preact/introduction] You don't have to do anything special to begin using the DOM.
[src:preact/introduction] You use the API directly in JavaScript from within what is called a *script*, a program run by a browser.
[src:preact/introduction] When you create a script, whether inline in a `<script>` element or included in the web page, you can immediately begin using the API for the `document` or `window` objects to manipulate the document itself, or any of the various elements in the web page (the descendant elements of the document).
[src:preact/introduction] As it is generally not recommended to mix the structure of the page (written in HTML) and manipulation of the DOM (written in JavaScript), the JavaScript parts will be grouped together here, and separated from the HTML.
[src:preact/introduction] This guide is about the objects and the actual *things* you can use to manipulate the DOM hierarchy.
[src:preact/introduction] There are many points where understanding how these work can be confusing.
[src:preact/introduction] For example, the object representing the HTML `form` element gets its `name` property from the `HTMLFormElement` interface but its `className` property from the `HTMLElement` interface.
[src:preact/introduction] In both cases, the property you want is in that form object.
[src:preact/introduction] But the relationship between objects and the interfaces that they implement in the DOM can be confusing, and so this section attempts to say a little something about the actual interfaces in the DOM specification and how they are made available.
[src:preact/introduction] Many objects implement several different interfaces.
[src:preact/introduction] The table object, for example, implements a specialized `HTMLTableElement` interface, which includes such methods as `createCaption` and `insertRow`.
[src:preact/introduction] But since it's also an HTML element, `table` implements the `Element` interface described in the DOM `Element` Reference chapter.
[src:preact/introduction] And finally, since an HTML element is also, as far as the DOM is concerned, a node in the tree of nodes that make up the object model for an HTML or XML page, the table object also implements the more basic `Node` interface, from which `Element` derives.
[src:preact/introduction] When you get a reference to a `table` object, as in the following example, you routinely use all three of these interfaces interchangeably on the object, perhaps without knowing it.
[src:preact/introduction] This page tries to describe the various objects and types in simple terms.
[src:preact/introduction] But there are a number of different data types being passed around the API that you should be aware of.
[src:preact/introduction] The following table briefly describes these data types.
[src:preact/introduction] There are also some common terminology considerations to keep in mind.
[src:preact/introduction] It's common to refer to any `Attr` node as an `attribute`, for example, and to refer to an array of DOM nodes as a `nodeList`.
[src:preact/introduction] You'll find these terms and others to be introduced and used throughout the documentation.
[src:preact/introduction] The `document` and `window` objects are the objects whose interfaces you generally use most often in DOM programming.
[src:preact/introduction] In simple terms, the `window` object represents something like the browser, and the `document` object is the root of the document itself.
[src:preact/introduction] `Element` inherits from the generic `Node` interface, and together these two interfaces provide many of the methods and properties you use on individual elements.
[src:preact/introduction] These elements may also have specific interfaces for dealing with the kind of data those elements hold, as in the `table` object example in the previous section.
[src:preact/introduction] The Document Object Model has been highly simplified.
[src:preact/introduction] To achieve this, the following interfaces in the different DOM level 3 or earlier specifications have been removed.
[src:preact/introduction] They are no longer available to web developers.
[src:preact/introduction] A document containing HTML is described using the `Document` interface, which is extended by the HTML specification to include various HTML-specific features.
[src:preact/introduction] In particular, the `Element` interface is enhanced to become `HTMLElement` and various subclasses, each representing one of (or a family of closely related) elements.
[src:preact/introduction] The HTML DOM API provides access to various browser features such as tabs and windows, CSS styles and stylesheets, browser history, etc.
[src:preact/introduction] These interfaces are discussed further in the HTML DOM API documentation.
[src:preact/introduction] Similarly, a document containing SVG is also described using the `Document` interface, which is extended by the SVG specification to include various SVG-specific features.
[src:preact/introduction] In particular, the `Element` interface is enhanced to become `SVGElement` and various subclasses, each representing an element or a family of closely related elements.
[src:preact/introduction] These interfaces are discussed further in the SVG API documentation.
[src:preact/introduction] This example uses a `<div>` element containing a `<textarea>` and two `<button>` elements.
[src:preact/introduction] When the user clicks the first button we set some text in the `<textarea>`.
[src:preact/introduction] When the user clicks the second button we clear the text.
[src:preact/introduction] This example uses a `<div>` element containing a `<div>` and two `<button>` elements.
[src:preact/introduction] When the user clicks the first button we create a new element and add it as a child of the `<div>`.
[src:preact/introduction] When the user clicks the second button we remove the child element.
[src:preact/introduction] Suppose the author wants to change the header of the document in What is a DOM tree? and write two paragraphs instead of one.
[src:preact/introduction] You can create the tree in What is a DOM tree? entirely in JavaScript too.
[src:preact/introduction] This example demonstrates how events fire and are handled in the DOM in a very simple way.
[src:preact/introduction] When the BODY of this HTML document loads, an event listener is registered with the top row of the TABLE.
[src:preact/introduction] The event listener handles the event by executing the function stopEvent, which changes the value in the bottom cell of the table.
[src:preact/introduction] However, stopEvent also calls an event object method, `event.stopPropagation`, which keeps the event from bubbling any further up into the DOM.
[src:preact/introduction] Note that the table itself has an `onclick` event handler that ought to display a message when the table is clicked.
[src:preact/introduction] But the stopEvent method has stopped propagation, and so after the data in the table is updated, the event phase is effectively ended, and an alert box is displayed to confirm this.
[src:preact/introduction] This example uses DOM methods to display all the properties of the `click` event object and their values in a table.
[src:preact/introduction] It also shows a useful technique of using a `for...in` loop to iterate over the properties of an object to get their values.
[src:preact/introduction] The properties of event objects differs greatly between browsers, the WHATWG DOM Standard lists the standard properties, however many browsers have extended these greatly.
[src:preact/introduction] Put the following code into a blank text file and load it into a variety of browsers, you'll be surprised at the different number and names of properties.
[src:preact/introduction] You might also like to add some elements in the page and call this function from different event handlers.
[src:preact/javascript-library] A **JavaScript library** is a library of pre-written JavaScript code that allows for easier development of JavaScript-based applications, especially for AJAX and other web-centric technologies.
[src:preact/javascript-library] They can be included in a website by embedding it directly in the HTML via a script tag.
[src:preact/javascript-library] With the expanded demands for JavaScript, an easier means for programmers to develop such dynamic interfaces was needed.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Thus, JavaScript libraries and JavaScript widget libraries were developed, allowing for developers to concentrate more upon more distinctive applications of Ajax.
[src:preact/javascript-library] This has led to other companies and groups, such as Microsoft and Yahoo! developing their own JavaScript-based user interface libraries, which find their way into the web applications developed by these companies.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Some JavaScript libraries allow for easier integration of JavaScript with other web development technologies, such as CSS, PHP, Ruby, and Java, while others provide utilities, often in the form of JavaScript functions, to make repetitive and complex tasks less taxing.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Many libraries include code to detect differences between runtime environments and remove the need for applications to allow for such inconsistencies.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Almost all JavaScript libraries are released under either a permissive or copyleft license to ensure license-free distribution, usage, and modification.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Some JavaScript libraries, such as Angular, are classified as frameworks since they exhibit full-stack capabilities and properties not found in general JavaScript libraries.
[src:preact/javascript-library] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:preact/javascript-library] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:preact/javascript-library] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:preact/javascript-library] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:preact/javascript-library] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:preact/javascript-library] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:preact/javascript-library] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:preact/javascript-library] All npm packages are JavaScript libraries, but not all libraries are packages.
[src:preact/javascript-library] Npm serves as a package manager for packages used in Node.js runtimes.
[src:preact/javascript-library] However, some npm packages offer CDN support for use of the library in both Node.js runtimes as well as the browser.
[src:preact/react-software] React can be used to develop single-page, mobile, or server-rendered applications with frameworks like Next.js and React Router.
[src:preact/react-software] Because React is only concerned with the user interface and rendering components to the DOM, React applications often rely on libraries for routing and other client-side functionality.
[src:preact/react-software] A key advantage of React is that it only re-renders those parts of the page that have changed, avoiding unnecessary re-rendering of unchanged DOM elements.
[src:preact/react-software] React is used by an estimated 6% of all websites.
[src:preact/react-software] React adheres to the declarative programming paradigm.
[src:preact/react-software] Developers design views for each state of an application, and React updates and renders components when data changes.
[src:preact/react-software] This is in contrast with imperative programming.
[src:preact/react-software] React code is made of entities called components.
[src:preact/react-software] These components are modular and can be reused.
[src:preact/react-software] React applications typically consist of many layers of components.
[src:preact/react-software] The components are rendered to a root element in the DOM using the React DOM library.
[src:preact/react-software] The two primary ways of declaring components in React are through function components and class components.
[src:preact/react-software] Since React v16.8, using function components is the recommended way.
[src:preact/react-software] Function components, announced at React Conf 2018, and available since React v16.8, are declared with a function that accepts a single "props" argument and returns JSX (JavaScript XML).
[src:preact/react-software] Function components can use internal state with the `useState` Hook.
[src:preact/react-software] On February 16, 2019, React 16.8 was released to the public, introducing React Hooks.
[src:preact/react-software] Hooks are functions that let developers "hook into" React state and lifecycle features from function components.
[src:preact/react-software] Notably, Hooks do not work inside classes — they let developers use more features of React without classes.
[src:preact/react-software] React provides several built-in hooks such as `useState`, `useContext`, `useReducer`, `useMemo` and `useEffect`.
[src:preact/react-software] Others are documented in the Hooks API Reference.
[src:preact/react-software] `useState` and `useEffect`, which are the most commonly used, are for controlling state and side effects, respectively.
[src:preact/react-software] "Only call hooks from React functions" — do not call hooks from plain JavaScript functions so that stateful logic stays with the component.
[src:preact/react-software] Although these rules cannot be enforced at runtime, code analysis tools such as linters can be configured to detect many mistakes during development.
[src:preact/react-software] The rules apply to both usage of Hooks and the implementation of custom Hooks, which may call other Hooks.
[src:preact/react-software] Though a similar concept to Server Side Rendering, RSCs do not send corresponding JavaScript to the client as no hydration occurs.
[src:preact/react-software] As a result, they have no access to hooks.
[src:preact/react-software] Class components are declared using ES6 classes.
[src:preact/react-software] They behave the same way that function components do, but instead of using Hooks to manage state and lifecycle events, they use the lifecycle methods on the `React.Component` base class.
[src:preact/react-software] React itself does not come with built-in support for routing.
[src:preact/react-software] React is primarily a library for building user interfaces, and it does not include a full-fledged routing solution out of the box.
[src:preact/react-software] Third-party libraries can be used to handle routing in React applications, such as React Router.
[src:preact/react-software] It allows the developer to define routes, manage navigation, and handle URL changes in a React-friendly way.
[src:preact/react-software] Another notable feature is the use of a virtual Document Object Model, or Virtual DOM.
[src:preact/react-software] React creates an in-memory data-structure, similar to the browser DOM.
[src:preact/react-software] Every time components are rendered, the result is compared with the virtual DOM.
[src:preact/react-software] It then updates the browser's displayed DOM efficiently with only the computed differences.
[src:preact/react-software] This process is called **reconciliation**.
[src:preact/react-software] This allows the programmer to write code as if the entire page is rendered on each change, while React only renders the components that actually change.
[src:preact/react-software] This selective rendering provides a major performance boost.
[src:preact/react-software] When `ReactDOM.render` is called again for the same component and target, React represents the new UI state in the Virtual DOM and determines which parts (if any) of the living DOM needs to change.
[src:preact/react-software] Lifecycle methods for class-based components use a form of hooking that allows the execution of code at set points during a component's lifetime.
[src:preact/react-software] JSX, or JavaScript XML, is an extension to the JavaScript language syntax.
[src:preact/react-software] Similar in appearance to HTML, JSX provides a way to structure component rendering using syntax familiar to many developers.
[src:preact/react-software] React components are typically written using JSX, although they do not have to be (components may also be written in pure JavaScript).
[src:preact/react-software] During compilation, JSX is converted to JavaScript code.
[src:preact/react-software] JSX is similar to another extension syntax created by Facebook for PHP called XHP.
[src:preact/react-software] The basic architecture of React applies beyond rendering HTML in the browser.
[src:preact/react-software] For example, Facebook has dynamic charts that render to `<canvas>` tags, and Netflix and PayPal use universal loading to render identical HTML on both the server and client.
[src:preact/react-software] React can also be used to develop native apps for Android and iOS using React Native.
[src:preact/react-software] Server-side rendering (SSR) refers to the process of rendering a client-side JavaScript application on the server, rather than in the browser.
[src:preact/react-software] This can improve the performance of the application, especially for users on slower connections or devices.
[src:preact/react-software] With SSR, the initial HTML that is sent to the client includes the fully rendered UI of the application.
[src:preact/react-software] This allows the client's browser to display the UI immediately, rather than having to wait for the JavaScript to download and execute before rendering the UI.
[src:preact/react-software] React supports SSR, which allows developers to render React components on the server and send the resulting HTML to the client.
[src:preact/react-software] This can be useful for improving the performance of the application, as well as for search engine optimization purposes.
[src:preact/react-software] React does not attempt to provide a complete application library.
[src:preact/react-software] It is designed specifically for building user interfaces and therefore does not include many of the tools some developers might consider necessary to build an application.
[src:preact/react-software] This allows the choice of whichever libraries the developer prefers to accomplish tasks such as performing network access or local data storage.
[src:preact/react-software] Common patterns of usage have emerged as the library matures.
[src:preact/react-software] To support React's concept of unidirectional data flow (which might be contrasted with AngularJS's bidirectional flow), the *Flux* architecture was developed as an alternative to the popular model–view–controller architecture.
[src:preact/react-software] Flux features *actions* which are sent through a central *dispatcher* to a *store*, and changes to the store are propagated back to the view.
[src:preact/react-software] When used with React, this propagation is accomplished through component properties.
[src:preact/react-software] Since its conception, Flux has been superseded by libraries such as Redux and MobX.
[src:preact/react-software] Flux can be considered a variant of the observer pattern.
[src:preact/react-software] A React component under the Flux architecture should not directly modify any props passed to it, but should be passed callback functions that create *actions* which are sent by the dispatcher to modify the store.
[src:preact/react-software] The action is an object whose responsibility is to describe what has taken place: for example, an action describing one user "following" another might contain a user id, a target user id, and the type `USER_FOLLOWED_ANOTHER_USER`.
[src:preact/react-software] The stores, which can be thought of as models, can alter themselves in response to actions received from the dispatcher.
[src:preact/react-software] This pattern is sometimes expressed as "properties flow down, actions flow up".
[src:preact/react-software] Many implementations of Flux have been created since its inception, perhaps the most well-known being Redux, which features a single store, often called a single source of truth.
[src:preact/react-software] In February 2019, `useReducer` was introduced as a React hook in the 16.8 release.
[src:preact/react-software] It provides an API that is consistent with Redux, enabling developers to create Redux-like stores that are local to component states.
[src:preact/react-software] React was created by Jordan Walke, a software engineer at Facebook, Inc.
[src:preact/react-software] (now Meta), who initially developed a prototype called "F-Bolt" before later renaming it to "FaxJS".
[src:preact/react-software] This early version is documented in Jordan Walke's GitHub repository.[1] Influences for the project included XHP, an HTML component library for PHP.
[src:preact/react-software] React was first deployed on Facebook's News Feed in 2011 and subsequently integrated into Instagram in 2012.
[src:preact/react-software] React Native, which enables native Android, iOS, and UWP development with React, was announced at Facebook's React Conf in February 2015 and open-sourced in March 2015.
[src:preact/react-software] On April 18, 2017, Facebook announced React Fiber, a new set of internal algorithms for rendering, as opposed to React's old rendering algorithm, Stack.
[src:preact/react-software] React Fiber was to become the foundation of any future improvements and feature development of the React library.
[src:preact/react-software] The actual syntax for programming with React does not change; only the way that the syntax is executed has changed.
[src:preact/react-software] React's old rendering system, Stack, was developed at a time when the focus of the system on dynamic change was not understood.
[src:preact/react-software] Stack was slow to draw complex animation, for example, trying to accomplish all of it in one chunk.
[src:preact/react-software] Fiber breaks down animation into segments that can be spread out over multiple frames.
[src:preact/react-software] Likewise, the structure of a page can be broken into segments that may be maintained and updated separately.
[src:preact/react-software] JavaScript functions and virtual DOM objects are called "fibers", and each can be operated and updated separately, allowing for smoother on-screen rendering.
[src:preact/react-software] On September 26, 2017, React 16.0 was released to the public.
[src:preact/react-software] React 16.0 introduced error boundaries, a new component type that catches JavaScript errors anywhere in its child tree and renders a fallback UI instead of crashing the app.
[src:preact/react-software] On October 20, 2020, the React team released React v17.0, notable as the first major release without major changes to the React developer-facing API.
[src:preact/react-software] On March 29, 2022, React 18 was released which introduced a new concurrent renderer, automatic batching and support for server side rendering with Suspense.
[src:preact/react-software] React 18 dropped support for Internet Explorer 11.
[src:preact/react-software] On December 5, 2024, React 19 was released.
[src:preact/react-software] This release introduced Actions, which simplify the process of making state updates using asynchronous functions rather than having to manually handle pending states, errors and optimistic updates.
[src:preact/react-software] React 19 also included support for server components and improved static site generation.
[src:preact/react-software] In October 2025, Meta announced that it would donate React, React Native, and JSX (JavaScript XML) to a new React Foundation, part of the Linux Foundation.
[src:preact/react-software] On 24 February 2026, The React Foundation officially launched with Meta Platforms, Inc. contributing the React project to the Foundation.
[src:preact/react-software] On 29 November 2025, a vulnerability CVE-2025-55182, also known as React2Shell was reported that allowed remote code execution.
[src:preact/react-software] It was assigned a CVSS highest score of 10.0.
[src:preact/react-software] On December 11, 2025, the React team disclosed additional vulnerabilities in React Server Components: denial-of-service issues (CVE-2025-55184 and CVE-2025-67779, CVSS 7.5) and a source code exposure issue (CVE-2025-55183, CVSS 5.3).
[src:preact/react-software] The initial public release of React in May 2013 used the Apache License 2.0.
[src:preact/react-software] Many expressed concerns that Facebook could unfairly exploit the termination clause or that integrating React into a product might complicate a startup company's future acquisition.
[src:preact/react-software] In August 2017, Facebook dismissed the Apache Foundation's downstream concerns and refused to reconsider their license.
[src:preact/react-software] The following month, WordPress decided to switch its Gutenberg and Calypso projects away from React.
[src:preact/react-software] On September 26, 2017, React 16.0.0 was released with the MIT license.
[src:preact/react-software] The MIT license change has also been backported to the 15.x release line with React 15.6.2.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] A **virtual DOM** is a lightweight JavaScript representation of the Document Object Model (DOM) used in declarative web frameworks such as React, Vue.js, and Elm.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] Since generating a virtual DOM is relatively fast, any given framework is free to rerender the virtual DOM as many times as needed relatively cheaply.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] The framework can then find the differences between the previous virtual DOM and the current one (diffing), and only makes the necessary changes to the actual DOM (reconciliation).
[src:preact/virtual-dom] While technically slower than using just vanilla JavaScript, the pattern makes it much easier to write websites with a lot of dynamic content, since markup is directly coupled with state.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] Similar techniques include Ember.js' Glimmer and Angular's incremental DOM.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] The JavaScript DOM API has historically been inconsistent across browsers, clunky to use, and difficult to scale for large projects.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] While libraries like jQuery aimed to improve the overall consistency and ergonomics of interacting with HTML, it too was prone to repetitive code that didn't describe the nature of the changes being made well and decoupled logic from markup.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] The release of AngularJS in 2010 provided a major paradigm shift in the interaction between JavaScript and HTML with the idea of dirty checking.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] Instead of imperatively declaring and destroying event listeners and modifying individual DOM nodes, changes in variables were tracked and sections of the DOM were invalidated and rerendered when a variable in their scope changed.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] This digest cycle provided a framework to write more declarative code that coupled logic and markup in a more logical way.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] While AngularJS aimed to provide a more declarative experience, it still required data to be explicitly bound to and watched by the DOM, and performance concerns were cited over the expensive process of dirty checking hundreds of variables.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] To alleviate these issues, React was the first major library to adopt a virtual DOM in 2013, which removed both the performance bottlenecks (since diffing and reconciling the DOM was relatively cheap) and the difficulty of binding data (since components were effectively just objects).
[src:preact/virtual-dom] Other benefits of a virtual DOM included improved security since XSS was effectively impossible and better extensibility since a component's state was entirely encapsulated.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] Its release also came with the advent of JSX, which further coupled HTML and JavaScript with an XML-like syntax extension.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] Following React's success, many other web frameworks copied the general idea of an ideal DOM representation in memory, such as Vue.js in 2014, which used a template compiler instead of JSX and had fine-grained reactivity built as part of the framework.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] In recent times, the virtual DOM has been criticized for being slow due to the additional time required for diffing and reconciling DOM nodes.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] This has led to the development of frameworks without a virtual DOM, such as Svelte, and frameworks that edit the DOM in-place such as Angular 2.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] React pioneered the use of a virtual DOM to make components declaratively.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] Virtual DOM nodes are constructed using the `createElement()` function, but are often transpiled from JSX to make writing components more ergonomic.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] In class-based React, virtual DOM nodes are returned from the `render()` function, while in functional hook-based components, the return value of the function itself serves as the page markup.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] Vue.js uses a virtual DOM to handle state changes, but is usually not directly interacted with; instead, a compiler is used to transform HTML templates into virtual DOM nodes as an implementation detail.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] While Vue supports writing JSX and custom render functions, it's more typical to use the template compiler since a build step isn't required that way.
[src:preact/virtual-dom] Svelte does not have a virtual DOM, with its creator Rich Harris calling the virtual DOM "pure overhead".
[src:preact/virtual-dom] Instead of diffing and reconciling DOM nodes at runtime, Svelte uses compile-time reactivity to analyze markup and generate JavaScript code that directly manipulates the DOM, drastically increasing performance.
